ling originally based on Marina Aisa's nuxt-markdown-blog"}]}},"_type":"markdown","_id":"content:blog:nuxt-content-blog.md","_source":"content","_file":"blog/nuxt-content-blog.md","_stem":"blog/nuxt-content-blog","_extension":"md"},{"_path":"/blog/polychrometext-introduction","_dir":"blog","_draft":false,"_partial":false,"_locale":"","title":"Introducing PolychromeText","description":"A browser-based text-drawing program because I was jealous of Jackson Pollock and Mark Rothko","headline":"PolychromeText","date":"2019-09-14T12:00:00","dateUpdated":"","author":"Michael Paulukonis","authorUrl":"https://michael.paulukonis.github.io/","socialImage":{"src":"/blog/media/polychrometext.thumb.jpg","mime":"webp","alt":"an older version of Polychrometext with some GUI elements","width":900,"height":583},"tags":["art","programming","text","pinned","p5js"],"body":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tag":"h1","props":{"id":"an-introduction-to-polychrometext"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"An introduction to PolychromeText"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"NOTE: as of 03.2025 this needs a massive update. As does the code."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"img","props":{"alt":"a working session of PolychromeText showing an older GUI","src":"/blog/media/polychrometext.thumb.jpg"},"children":[]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h2","props":{"id":"what-are-you-talking-about"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"What are you talking about?"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"a","props":{"href":"https://michaelpaulukonis.github.io/polychrome.p5/","rel":["noopener","noreferer"],"target":"_blank"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"THIS"}]},{"type":"text","value":" is PolychromeText - a text-painter web-app."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Ever since I was a wee nipper, I've wanted to be able to create with text the way Jackson Pollock created with paint:\ndripping, flinging, pouring, etc."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Andy Warhol and Mark Rothko are also influences in various ways. Warhol's screen-prints led me to think how \"text\" is almost infinitely repeatable, and thus not a comodity, like a painting or a print could be. That led me down many roads with physical concrete poetry, typewriters and text paintings. Rothko is perhaps a more oblique influence, but he was me entree to color-field painting, and how several of my college classmates couldn't stand abstract paintings like that - their irritated descriptions filled me with a desire to create something similarly monolithic. I don't think I ever really did anything over-all until recently)."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"In early 2014 I took a \"MOOC\" on Processing, and one of my exercises became Polychrometext, so-named since it's second-week of life (it had a brief life as \"Text-Painter\" which is accurate if prosaic). I used the \"Javascript Mode\" to bring the sketch to the web. Eventually, I converted it to use Processing.js, and in 2018 moved on to p5js."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"The app has continued to evolve, perhaps slowly, as I continue to simultaneously \"focus\" on both the output and the internals - I "},{"type":"element","tag":"em","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"am"}]},{"type":"text","value":" a programmer during the day, and \"good\" code is important to me. Working on this project is a chance to express my viusal sense, but also exercise my code-skills. That said, I wouldn't necessarily hold it up as a stellar example of my work - it is highly unplanned and imperfect, filled with comments and side-tracks. Hopefully, it does show several things that I care about, and I would encourage anybody who wants to have a long-lived creative-coding project to realize that organizing the code makes it so much easier to grow your code."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"a","props":{"href":"https://www.instagram.com/explore/tags/polychrometext/","rel":["noopener","noreferer"],"target":"_blank"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Instragram posts"}]},{"type":"text","value":"."}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Most of them are also dumped into "},{"type":"element","tag":"a","props":{"href":"https://www.flickr.com/photos/othermichael/albums/72157641585339145","rel":["noopener","noreferer"],"target":"_blank"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Flickr"}]},{"type":"text","value":"."}]}],"toc":{"title":"","searchDepth":2,"depth":2,"links":[{"id":"what-are-you-talking-about","depth":2,"text":"What are you talking about?"}]}},"_type":"markdown","_id":"content:blog:polychrometext-introduction.md","_source":"content","_file":"blog/polychrometext-introduction.md","_stem":"blog/polychrometext-introduction","_extension":"md"},{"_path":"/blog/publications","_dir":"blog","_draft":false,"_partial":false,"_locale":"","title":"Publications","description":"Places that have graced me with my presence","headline":"Publications","date":"2021-07-01","dateUpdated":"","author":"Michael Paulukonis","socialImage":{"src":"/blog/media/publications.thumb.png","mime":"png","alt":"an online web zine","width":586,"height":413},"tags":["publications","writing","poetry","art","pinned"],"body":{"type":"root","children":[{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"NOTE: this is quite out-of-date and is a WIP"}]},{"type":"element","tag":"p","props":{},"children":[{"type":"element","tag":"img","props":{"alt":"fragment of Backslash Lit No.4","src":"/blog/media/publications.thumb.png"},"children":[]}]},{"type":"element","tag":"h2","props":{"id":"places-i-can-or-have-been-found"},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"